{"key":"processedPost-12637172","value":{"id":12637172,"first":12636930,"last":12637212,"when":1274972476,"utime":"05/27/10 06:01 PM","content":"One should never case after first flush.&nbsp; It's normal for contaminant spores to land on a substrate during the course of a flush, where they sit harmlessly.&nbsp; However, if you put a casing layer over these contaminant spores, you protect them and keep them nice and moist, allowing germination and the ruining of your project.<br />All bulk substrates should be pasteurized.&nbsp; If using anything but coir, it should be maintained at 140F to 160F for a full hour.&nbsp; Don't ever pour boiling water on compost, manure or straw.<br />RR","title":"Re: Can you case an entire monotub after the first flush?"}}